Copper supports two primary authentication methods: API Keys and OAuth 2.0 [1].

For the Platform API, you must use an API Key by including three specific headers in every request [2][3]:

Authorization: ApiKey {your_api_key}
X-Timestamp: {current_unix_timestamp_in_milliseconds}
X-Signature: {hmac_sha256_signature}

The signature is generated by concatenating the timestamp, uppercase HTTP method, request path (including parameters), and the request body, then signing the result with your API Secret using HMAC SHA256 and encoding it in hexadecimal [2][3].

For partner integrations, OAuth 2.0 is the preferred method using the Authorization Code Grant flow to obtain a Bearer token [1][4].
